<button class="accordion">What is instructional business writing?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>Instructional business writing provides the reader with the information needed to complete a task. The task may need to be accomplished immediately, or it may be for future reference.
This type of document must break down a process into steps that are understandable to the reader. The written record must account for the reader's knowledge of the area, the scope of the task while integrating variations or potential problems.</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">What are the examples of instructional business writing?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>Examples of instructional business writing are:</p>
<li>User manual</li>
<li>Specifications</li>
<li>Memo</li>
</div>
<button class="accordion">What is the specification in instructional business writing?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>An instructional business writing is a technical document which provides an outline of a product or process that allows it to be constructed or reconstructed by an unfamiliar but knowledgeable user, enabling effective distribution.</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">What is a memo in instructional business writing?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>A short notification of new information shared within a large group in an organisation. The memo may include direct instruction or be a reference on how to complete future tasks.</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">What is informational business writing?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>Not all business writing requires action. It created a large volume of writing for reference or record. This category can include some of the less glamorous but still essential documents. Recording business information accurately and consistently is essential for marking progress, predicting future work, as well as complying with legal and contractual obligations.</p>
